    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1888-06-07T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1888-06-07T00:00:00-05:00" n="213" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d213">
                <head>No. 213.<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Bayard</persName>
                            to Mr. <persName type="to">Denby</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department
                                    of State</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1888-06-07">
                            <hi rend="italic">June</hi> 7,
                            1888</date>.</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 327.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have received your No. 628 of April 17,
                        1888, in regard to the inquiry of the vice-consul at New-chwang as to the
                        treatment of American citizens engaged in smuggling contraband goods in
                        China and your reply that no law was provided for the punishment of such
                        offenders personally.</p>
                <p>As you say, “confiscation of the smuggled goods is the only penalty I [you]
                        know of,” and that is to be applied by China under her own revenue laws.
                        This point was made clear in the Department’s recent correspondence with you
                        about the opium smuggling act approved February 23, 1887<note n="*" xml:id="d213fn1">Printed in <ref target="frus1887#pg_225">Foreign
                                Relations, 1887, pages 225</ref>, <ref target="frus1887#pg_237">237</ref>–<ref target="frus1887#pg_243">243</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>I am, etc.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">T. F.
                            Bayard.</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
